    <fr:title text="dense subsite of affine opens">dense subsite of affine opens</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-000R/" title="scheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-000R/" display-uri="algm-000R" type="local">scheme</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the underlying locale (equipped with the canonical coverage) has a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0021/" title="dense subsite" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0021/" display-uri="algm-0021" type="local">dense subsite</fr:link> whose objects are affine opens, and morphisms are distinguished open subspaces. Note that this isn’t a full subcategory, since <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0020/" title="a non-distinguished affine subscheme" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0020/" display-uri="algm-0020" type="local">there exist affine open subspaces that are not distinguished</fr:link>.
</html:p>
    <html:p>
  Since schemes are covered by affine schemes, and distinguished opens form a basis in the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0007/" title="localic spectrum of a commutative ring" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0007/" display-uri="algm-0007" type="local">localic spectrum of a commutative ring</fr:link>, every open in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is covered by affine opens. On the other hand, <fr:link href="/forest/algm-0016/" title="Nike’s trick" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-0016/" display-uri="algm-0016" type="local">Nike’s trick</fr:link> guarantees the condition on morphisms for dense subsites.
</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
